<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="149" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="149">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="149">
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName authority="Latreille, 1802" authorityName="Rosa, Proshchalykin &amp; Halada" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Hedychridium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hedychridium weii" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">Hedychridium weii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(masculine noun in genitive) is dedicated to Na-sen 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Nelson”">&quot;Nelson&quot;</normalizedToken>
Wei (Guanghzou, China), for his contributions to the study of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysididae</taxonomicName>
of Inner Mongolia and China and his kind support to the studies of the first author.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="149" type="comparative diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="149">Comparative diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="149">
We describe 
<taxonomicName authority="Latreille, 1802" authorityName="Rosa, Proshchalykin &amp; Halada" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Hedychridium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hedychridium weii" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">Hedychridium weii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. in the 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. femoratum" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" rank="species" species="femoratum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">H. femoratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. It is closely related to 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. femoratum" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" rank="species" species="femoratum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">H. femoratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for its general habitus, yet it is separated by sparser mesonotal punctures, shape of genital capsule (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Hedychridium weii sp. nov., male, holotype A habitus, dorsal view B head, frontal view C genital capsule D habitus, lateral view E right antenna, lateral view F metasoma, postero-lateral view G metasoma, ventral view. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1068.73549.figure16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/608683" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">16C</figureCitation>
), elongate shape of the black spot on metatibia (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Hedychridium weii sp. nov., male, holotype A habitus, dorsal view B head, frontal view C genital capsule D habitus, lateral view E right antenna, lateral view F metasoma, postero-lateral view G metasoma, ventral view. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1068.73549.figure16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/608683" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">16F</figureCitation>
) and darker mesosoma colouration. It is separated from the other two newly- described species in this species group, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. splendens" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">H. splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. and 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. jacobsi" pageId="0" pageNumber="149" rank="species" species="jacobsi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="149">H. jacobsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., by flagellomeres black, different genital capsule and different shape of black spots on metatibia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
